        <div type="letter">
            <div type="text">
                <opener>
                    <placeName>Down, Beckenham, Kent</placeName>
                    <date>Nov: 13. 1876</date>
                    <salute>My dear Sir</salute>
                </opener>
                <div type="transcription">
                     
<p>I thank you cordially for your most kind present of your “Studien &amp;c”.— I look forward with extreme curiosity to learn the meaning of the wonderful and beautiful pictures of caterpillars, and I have no doubt that you will throw much light on this subject as you have on every one which you have investigated.<ref target="#foot.f1"/></p>
<p>With the greatest respect, I remain | Yours faithfully and obliged | Charles Darwin</p> 
                </div>
            </div>

            
        </div>

        

        

        <div type="footnotes">
            <note xml:id="foot.f1">There is an annotated copy of the second part of Weismann’s <hi rend="italic">Studien zur Decendenz-Theorie</hi> (Studies on the theory of descent; <ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_9324.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">Weismann 1876</ref>) in the Darwin Library–CUL (see <ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_5214.xml" resp="#mjhawkins"><hi rend="italic">Marginalia</hi></ref> 1: 856–7); the first part of the book was on caterpillars.</note>
        </div>        
            
